gain is 'iret', afaik. Of course,<br />it can be *any* iret, so once you enable interrupts, you can get a<br />timer interrupt, and the timer interrupt returning with iret will<br />re-enable NMI's then too.<br /><br />I would suggest that the actual NMI handler itself should probably<br />never use that paranoid exit at all, and just always use a regular<br />iret. Screw scheduling and TIF checks.<br /><br />Probably only the exceptions that can happen *during* NMI (eg debug,<br />stack exception, double-fault etc) should use the paranoid versions<br />that try to avoid using iret.<br /><br />Because I think you're right - we shouldn't call schedule() from<br />within the NMI handler, even if we do enable interrupts and switch to<br />the normal stack. Even if it probably does happen to work normally.<br /><br />But I have to admit to not necessarily thinking it through a lot.<br /><br />                            Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
